index 0000000..19dc9f2
--- /dev/null
+++ b/contrib/pgvector/bench/README.md
@@ -0,0 +1,137 @@
+# pgvector IVFFlat Benchmark
+
+This directory contains a reproducible benchmark harness for pgvector IVFFlat
+query performance. It measures the latency and recall trade-off for L2, inner
+product, and cosine distance with different `lists` and `probes` settings.
+
+The benchmark is intentionally separate from regression tests. It is designed
+for development and tuning, where results depend on hardware, data size, and
+runtime settings.
+
+## Requirements
+
+- A running OpenTenBase/PostgreSQL-compatible instance
+- `psql` in `PATH`
+- The `vector` extension installed and available in the target database
+
+## Quick Start
+
+Run all three vector metrics with the default settings:
+
+```bash
+cd contrib/pgvector
+bench/run_ivfflat_benchmark.sh
+```
+
+Run a smaller smoke benchmark:
+
+```bash
+ROWS=1000 DIMS=32 QUERIES=5 LISTS=10 PROBES_LIST="1 4 10" \
+  bench/run_ivfflat_benchmark.sh
+```
+
+Run only cosine distance:
+
+```bash
+METRICS=cosine ROWS=100000 DIMS=384 LISTS=100 PROBES_LIST="1 4 10 32 100" \
+  bench/run_ivfflat_benchmark.sh
+```
+
+Load the recommendation helper:
+
+```bash
+psql -d postgres -f bench/ivfflat_recommendation.sql
+```
+
+Recommend an initial IVFFlat setting for a target recall:
+
+```sql
+SELECT *
+FROM pgvector_bench.recommend_ivfflat_params(
+  row_count => 100000,
+  dims => 128,
+  target_recall => 0.90,
+  metric => 'cosine'
+);
+```
+
+The script generates deterministic CSV data files, loads them with server-side
+`COPY`, runs exact and IVFFlat queries from the client, and writes a CSV report
+to:
+
+```text
+bench/results/ivfflat_benchmark_<timestamp>.csv
+```
+
+It also writes an `EXPLAIN` report for each metric to:
+
+```text
+bench/results/ivfflat_benchmark_<timestamp>_plans.txt
+```
+
+## Environment Variables
+
+| Variable | Default | Description |
+| --- | --- | --- |
+| `DBNAME` | `postgres` | Database name |
+| `PGHOST` | unset | Passed through to `psql` |
+| `PGPORT` | unset | Passed through to `psql` |
+| `PGUSER` | unset | Passed through to `psql` |
+| `ROWS` | `10000` | Number of vectors in the benchmark table |
+| `DIMS` | `128` | Vector dimensions |
+| `QUERIES` | `20` | Number of query vectors |
+| `TOPK` | `10` | Number of nearest neighbors |
+| `LISTS` | `100` | IVFFlat list count |
+| `PROBES_LIST` | `1 4 10 32 100` | Probe values to test |
+| `METRICS` | `l2 ip cosine` | Distance metrics to run |
+| `MAINTENANCE_WORK_MEM` | `512MB` | Session memory used while building IVFFlat indexes |
+| `OUTPUT` | auto-generated | CSV output path |
+| `PLAN_OUTPUT` | derived from `OUTPUT` | EXPLAIN plan output path |
+
+## Metrics
+
+The report contains:
+
+- `avg_latency_ms`: average query latency across query vectors
+- `p95_latency_ms`: p95 query latency across query vectors
+- `recall_at_k`: average overlap between exact top-k results and IVFFlat top-k
+- `exact_avg_latency_ms`: average exact scan latency with index scans disabled
+
+Recall is calculated as:
+
+```text
+recall@k = |exact_top_k intersect index_top_k| / k
+```
+
+## Parameter Recommendation
+
+`ivfflat_recommendation.sql` creates two objects:
+
+- `pgvector_bench.ivfflat_benchmark_observations`: measured benchmark
+  observations that can seed recommendations.
+- `pgvector_bench.recommend_ivfflat_params(...)`: returns recommended
+  `lists`, `probes`, expected recall/latency when measured data exists,
+  suggested `maintenance_work_mem`, and a risk label.
+
+The helper uses measured observations first. If no observation matches the
+requested `row_count`, `dims`, `metric`, and `lists`, it falls back to a
+conservative heuristic and returns `recommendation_source = 'heuristic'`.
+Heuristic results are starting points, not production guarantees.
+
+## Notes
+
+- Exact results are collected with index scans disabled, so they are not
+  affected by approximate index scans. The exact baseline is still collected
+  after index creation; the planner is constrained for correctness comparison.
+- The plan report captures one indexed query per metric and should show an
+  `Index Scan` using `items_embedding_ivfflat_idx`.
+- Benchmark queries order only by the vector distance expression. Adding a
+  secondary sort key such as `id` can prevent IVFFlat from being selected.
+- The script recreates the `pgvector_bench` schema in the target database.
+- For cosine distance, zero vectors are avoided because they are not indexed.
+- Large `ROWS` and `LISTS` values may need a larger `MAINTENANCE_WORK_MEM`
+  during index creation.
+- The benchmark is client-driven to avoid OpenTenBase pull-up function limits
+  for DML statements in distributed execution.
+- Use this benchmark to compare commits, parameter settings, and hardware. Do
+  not use a single run as a universal performance claim.
diff --git a/contrib/pgvector/bench/ivfflat_benchmark.sql b/contrib/pgvector/bench/ivfflat_benchmark.sql
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..5198cbb
--- /dev/null
+++ b/contrib/pgvector/bench/ivfflat_benchmark.sql
@@ -0,0 +1,24 @@
+\set ON_ERROR_STOP on
+
+DROP SCHEMA IF EXISTS pgvector_bench CASCADE;
+CREATE SCHEMA pgvector_bench;
+SET search_path = pgvector_bench, public;
+SET maintenance_work_mem = :'maintenance_work_mem';
+
+CREATE EXTENSION IF NOT EXISTS vector;
+
+CREATE TABLE items (
+    id integer PRIMARY KEY,
+    embedding vector(:dims)
+);
+
+COPY items(id, embedding) FROM '__ITEMS_FILE__' WITH (FORMAT csv);
+
+ANALYZE items;
+
+CREATE INDEX items_embedding_ivfflat_idx
+ON items
+USING ivfflat (embedding :opclass)
+WITH (lists = :lists);
+
+ANALYZE items;
